english:
  title: 'On the Restoration of the Avalokiteśvara Statue at Naksan: A Record and Eulogy'
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: "Along the shores of the Eastern Sea stands Naksan, where there exists a sacred realm—pristine and dust-free, where the water-moon reflection dwells in clarity. Yet alas, those savage invaders, so brutish and ignorant, came sweeping through with fire and sword, leaving no temple untouched, no Buddha's form unbroken. Even the Great Saint's divine body fell victim to their ravage. Though the form yet remains, the precious treasures housed within the belly were utterly exposed and scattered, leaving only emptiness. \n\nYet we know that the Awakened mind transcends all notions of fullness and emptiness, of gain and loss. The Diamond Body cannot truly be destroyed. And yet, to the eyes of ordinary mortals like us, is it not a cause of deepest sorrow? For one such as this disciple, whose reverence has grown only deeper with time, hearing of these sacred contents scattered to the winds—how could I not feel this pain as though it were my own, and move with urgency to restore what was lost?\n\nTherefore, with careful deliberation, I have gathered from the old records two celestial mirrors, five fragrances, five medicines, colored silks, and brocade pouches—all these offerings—to fill the hollow sanctuary once more. What was broken is made whole again. What was lost is returned. Is there any blemish remaining?\n\nMy prayer is this: Let all beings turn their hearts in reverence.\n\n*In verse I sing:*\n\nWhat cannot be destroyed at last\nIs the true diamond body—\nBut all that stands in form without,\nIs made and marred by human hand.\nHumans are not all the same:\nSome bow in reverence, some in scorn.\nThose who scorn bring ruin;\nI who revere bring restoration.\nAs the moon grows dark and thin,\nSo too shall it wax full again.\nLet all good men and women\nTurn their hearts as one in faith."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Naksan refers to the sacred mountain in what is now Gangwon Province, Korea, site of the famous Naksan Temple dedicated to Avalokiteśvara (the Bodhisattva of Compassion).
  - key: ''
    value: The 'belly' (腹藏, bokjang) refers to the interior cavity of Buddhist statues, traditionally filled with sacred texts, relics, and ritual objects as part of their consecration.
  - key: ''
    value: The Diamond Body (金剛眞體) refers to the indestructible, ultimate nature of Buddhist reality, which transcends physical form and destruction.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gyeongbo (1168-1241) was a Goryeo-period scholar-official and poet, known for synthesizing Confucian, Buddhist, and Daoist thought.
